node.text:
Running a 10.3 MK18 from close out to 400m with a Razor 1-6 HD II. While short barrels aren’t optimal for longer ranges, it can still be done. Good ammo and knowing your holds helps. I’m using 55g Winchester ball which… isn’t the best for this. But still doable. This is one of my favorite LPVOs as it has the brightest center dot of any scope I’ve used.
-
Got them in stock at @trexarms
-

node.text:
One of my favorite things about the new Sidecar is how awesome it is at 3-5 o’clock. Why would you want this in conjunction with a plate carrier? Well… sometimes a full warbelt isn’t the best option. Maybe you’re throwing kit on later in the day. Or you’re working in/around vehicles consistently with light armor on. Options are good to have as things change/develop. The new generation of Sidecar supports these options much more efficiently.
-
That’s what we’re all about.
-

node.text:
Shot-calling is something every basic carbine/pistol class should cover. It is essential for self-diagnosis in improving marksmanship, recoil control, and shooting speed. I don’t think certain skills make someone “advanced” or “level 2” but if there was one thing that elevates some shooters above others, it’s shot-calling. Make sure you shoot a target far enough away so you can’t see the impact before you walk up. This is why I like to go back 25m+, make my call, then walk up and paste hits.
-
This is a segment from my 3 hour carbine class that is available for free at TREX-ARMS.COM.
-

node.text:
The NRA is most responsible for continually neutering every generation of gun owner since it’s inception. The above image within the meme is a post from their Facebook page yesterday; caving to the rhetoric of the anti-gun crowd, and supporting the concept that civilians SHOULDN’T own weapons of war. It’s this line of thinking that gets people comfortable saying “well, we don’t NEED AR pistols, bump stocks, or semi-auto 5.56 rifles since civilians don’t need weapons of war and CNN is telling me that’s what these things are for. So let’s ban them”.
-
Here is the conversation that needs to be happening to prevent further regulation and enable us to win BACK rights instead of simply begging for money every year, losing some rights, using said lost rights to create antithesis to beg for more money, reward donors with a bag from China, etc:
-
1. Government should NOT hold a monopoly on violence.
2. Citizens should own, manage, and possess weapons for war. For the sake of national security regarding foreign invasion, holding our own government accountable, and protecting ourselves in everyday life.
3. AR15s are absolutely a “weapon of war”. Generally with very few differences than the M4s used by most NATO allies and our own military. In fact, some AR15s are better quality and more effective than “military M4” rifles. AR/M4 = same thing. Only difference is a lack of select-fire.
4. Full auto is simply angry splits. Should be available to citizens and in weapons wherever needed/desired.
-
You’ll never hear the NRA say any of this stuff. People say it’s because “it’s too extreme” but the question is; WHY are these points considered “extreme”? What got us to think they’re extreme? Who’s responsible for that? 
-

-

There has been a pretty serious disconnect between gun owners who own guns for the sake of owning guns, and gun owners who own guns because of the intended purpose of the Second Amendment. The purpose of our latest video was to address the idea of viewing long guns as being part of broader system. Featuring a symbiotic relationship with support equipment to further the capability of you AND the weapon. Sure you can stuff mags into each of your pants pockets, but is that more effective than a optimized dedicated mag-carrying piece of gear? Absolutely not. Support gear should go hand-in-hand with long guns if your goal is 2A and civil-unrest preparedness (see 2020). Logistics is key.
-
Check out the rest of this video on the @trexarms YouTube channel.

node.text:
Throughout the budget vs Gucci conversation, there are a lot of people who claim their budget builds are “just as good” as more expensive builds without clear metrics or science to back up WHY their budget rifle is better than say a LMT. The only metric they have is cost. Which is a very emotional metric and why many people feel it’s enough. But the bigger question should be: what is your life worth? If riots came to your city tomorrow, and things were wonky for 6+ months, and you’re carrying and potentially using your rifle often; do you want to gamble with a product that has less QC checks? Worse tolerances? And lower quality metals and parts? If you had to race your car tomorrow in a matter of life-and-death, you’d probably want a nice car, not some beater from the car lot sold by a shady salesman with a top hat.
-
On the flip side, there are plenty of “Gucci” companies that overcharge for benefit (or perceived benefit). Does twice the cost get you twice the performance? Not necessarily. But big name companies which professionals routinely pick are generally companies with a big name for a reason. Quality. Credibility. Consistency. SOCOM does not buy or issue PSAs, Sports, DoubleStars, etc… now, we shouldn’t necessarily copy all of their requirements or NEED to emulate every standard they have, but it can be an indicator.
-
If you can only afford a budget rifle right now, that’s better than nothing. Get one and train. But set a goal for better gear. Finer weapons.
-
Our latest YouTube video addresses much of this and more. With demos!
-

node.text:
Can a budget rifle be put to work? Yes. Skills is what matter. But there’s a reason nicer gear exists… it’s nicer. More reliable. Lasts longer. More accurate. Repeatable. Consistent. This M&P sport did fine for me shooting 680ish rounds over two days… but will it be just as fine after 2k? 4k? 10k? Lots of gun owners say their budget rifle “has been just fine for me”, but by what metrics? A few range days? Leaning up next to your bed? Sitting in the safe doing nothing? Time on the gun and round count doesn’t lie… that’s what makes or breaks good and bad rifles.
-
Full video is up on YouTube titled: “Can you Build a Rifle for $1000?”
